<TITLE> Cabinet decides to cut diesel costs </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 7 (bdnews24.com)  The first meeting of Sheikh Hasina's new cabinet on Wednesday decided to increase fertiliser subsidies, cut diesel prices and press on with the anti-terror and anti-criminal efforts. To distribute fertilisers among the farmers easily, the meeting decided to revive the fertiliser distribution method followed during the 1996-2001 AL administration. The meeting also decided to provide fulltime security, residence, health and other facilities to outgoing chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed for one year. All the cabinet members took part in the meeting, chaired by prime minister Sheikh Hasina at her office. Citing the recent reports of violence at places in the country, the meeting directed the law-enforcement agencies to take stern actions to prevent a repeat. It also ordered them to gather intelligence and maintain security at educational institutions and provide security to people's life and properties. The prime minister's advisers, cabinet secretary and secretaries of ministries and divisions also attended the meeting. Earlier, a top aide said the meeting would make decisions on law and order and agricultural production. "Before the formal cabinet meeting, the prime minister will sit with cabinet members informally," secretary Kazi Aminul Islam at the Prime Minister's Office said. "The meeting will also discuss security for former chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed," he had said. bdnews24.com/ahd/nju/ac/m
